Climate Change: Study temperature and precipitation in historical vs contemporary weather records¶

STAT 201  Project Proposal - Group 17
Date:         April 09, 2022

Introduction¶

Climate change refers to long-term shifts in temperatures and weather patterns (United Nations, n.d.-b). Although the main cause for climate change varies from the rising concentration of greenhouse gases in the atmosphere to periodical change in solar activities and remains controversial, the effects of climate change are more universally observed. United Nations (n.d.-a) summarizes the effects of climate change as: hotter temperatures, more severe storms, increased drought, etc. We intend to obtain data from a Canadian weather station and study the presence of these effects of climate change by comparing historical data with the present.

The Canadian Climate and Weather Database provides weather records from numerous weather stations across Canada. Each weather station contains weather records in hourly, daily, and monthly formats. In order to obtain a meaningful and relatively large time span, the group queried stations with data available between 1950 and 2022. The query returned 8796 weather stations, from which, we randomly selected ABBOTSFORD A weather station in BC to use for this study (Historical Data, 2021, November 25).

We intend to choose daily temperature and precipitation as the random variables separated into two categories - historical vs contemporary. For temperature, the variable is the daily temperature, and we want to study the parameter mean. We believe this can aid us to study the claimed effect of hotter temperatures. For precipitation, the variable is yearly maximum rainfall. We also study the parameter mean to evaluate the claimed effect of increased drought (United Nations, n.d.-a). Thus, this project aims to answer:

Are there significant differences in the weather record of the 1950s and the 2000s in terms of temperature and rainfall?

Overview¶

Table 1 summarizes the abbreviation used in this report:

Abbreviation Parameter
$\mu_{ct}$ mean of the contemporary daily mean temperature
$\mu_{ht}$ mean of the historical daily mean temperature
$\mu_{cr}$ mean of the contemporary yearly maximum rainfall
$\mu_{ht}$ mean of the historical yearly maximum rainfall
$\bar{x}_{ct}$ sample mean of the contemporary daily mean temperature
$\bar{x}_{ht}$ sample mean of the historical daily mean temperature
$\bar{x}_{cr}$ sample mean of the contemporary yearly maximum rainfall
$\bar{x}_{ht}$ sample mean of the historical yearly maximum rainfall

Table 1. Table of abbreviation.

The first hypothesis we test is:
Test Statistic: The difference in sample mean $\bar{x}_{ct} - \bar{x}_{ht}$
Null Hypothesis: The difference in population mean of the contemporary daily mean temperature and the historical daily mean temperature is zero.
Alternative Hypothesis: The difference in population mean of the contemporary daily mean temperature and the historical daily mean temperature is not zero.

$$H_0^{1}: \mu_{ct} - \mu_{ht} = 0$$

$$H_A^{1}: \mu_{ct} - \mu_{ht} \neq 0$$

The second hypothesis we test is:
Test Statistic: The difference in sample mean $\bar{x}_{cr} - \bar{x}_{hr}$
Null Hypothesis: The difference in population mean of the contemporary maximum yearly rainfall and the historical maximum yearly rainfall is zero.
Alternative Hypothesis: The difference in population mean of the contemporary maximum yearly rainfall and the historical maximum yearly rainfall is not zero.

$$H_0^{2}: \mu_{cr} - \mu_{hr} = 0$$

$$H_A^{2}: \mu_{cr} - \mu_{hr} \neq 0$$

We test the hypotheses in two ways: bootstrap simulation and asymptotic two-sample t-test and choose a significant value of $\alpha$ = 0.05 as a standard value in the statistics field.

Methods¶

Data Importing, Cleaning, and Wrangling¶

We first download and import daily data from 1950 to 1969 and 2000 to 2019.

The raw sample contains 31 variables of weather measurements in which we decide to use the following as our possible parameters:

  • Year: the year of the weather record
  • Max Temp: the maximum temperature of the day in degrees Celsius.
  • Min Temp: the minimum temperature of the day in degrees Celsius.
  • Mean Temp: the average temperature of the day in degrees Celsius.
  • Total Rain: the total amount of rain of the day measured in millimetres.
  • Total Precip: the total amount of precipitation of the day measured in millimetres.

Temperature¶

The United Nations (n.d.-a) states that the temperature in the recent decade is higher than last century. Is there enough evidence to support this claim? Can we see this claimed difference in Mean_Temp between historical and contemporary data in the sample weather records from the Abbotsford A weather station? We first visualize the categorical difference in Mean_Temp with a box plot.

In [4]:

    select(Mean_Temp, Category)

temp_boxplot <- station_temp %>%

temp_boxplot

Figure 1. Boxplot of daily mean temperature at Abbotsford A weather station

From this boxplot, we can observe that there is a small difference in the median of daily Mean_Temp between the historical and contemporary weather records. However, is there a real difference in the mean of the daily temperature? We answer the question by performing a hypothesis test:

$$H_0^{1}: \mu_{ct} - \mu_{ht} = 0$$

$$H_A^{1}: \mu_{ct} - \mu_{ht} \neq 0$$

We begin by visualizing the sample distribution.

Temperature - Bootstrap Simulation¶

The first method we use to test this hypothesis is the simulation based permutation with the infer package. We first calculate the observed test statistic, then generate a simulation from the null distribution. We further obtain the P-value. The following codes demonstrate the steps:

In [6]:
set.seed(100)
options(repr.plot.width = 10, repr.plot.height = 6)

obs_diff_in_temp <- station_temp %>%
    specify(formula = Mean_Temp ~ Category) %>%
    calculate(stat = "diff in means", order = c("contemporary", "historical"))

null_diff_in_temp <- station_temp %>%
    specify(formula = Mean_Temp ~ Category) %>%
    hypothesize(null = "independence") %>%
    generate(reps = 1000, type = "permute") %>%
    calculate(stat = "diff in means", order = c("contemporary", "historical"))

diff_in_temp_plot <- null_diff_in_temp %>%
    visualize(bins = 10) +
    shade_p_value(obs_stat = obs_diff_in_temp, direction = "both") +
    xlab("Difference between sample means (°C)") +
    theme(text = element_text(size = 20))
diff_in_temp_plot

p_value <- null_diff_in_temp %>%
    get_p_value(obs_stat = obs_diff_in_temp, direction = "both")

Warning message:
“Please be cautious in reporting a p-value of 0. This result is an approximation based on the number of `reps` chosen in the `generate()` step. See `?get_p_value()` for more information.”

Figure 3. Figure of simulation distribution and P-value of the daily temperature hypothesis test.

Notice that the red line in the above graph indicates the observed difference in temperature, which is far out of the range of values generated by simulation under the null hypothesis, suggesting that the null hypothesis might possibly be rejected. To further prove this, we notice that the simulation returned a p-value of 0; however, we should never report a p-value of 0 because this suggests that making a Type I error is impossible. Since we used 1000 reps to calculate the sample, we conclude:

The p-value is < 0.001, we reject the null hypothesis $H_0^1$ in favor of $H_A^1$ at the 5% significant level.

We further compute the 95% confidence interval of this observed test statistic using the bootstrap method.

In [7]:
options(repr.plot.width = 10, repr.plot.height = 6)
set.seed(100)
diff_in_temp_bootstrap_dist <- station_temp %>%
    specify(formula = Mean_Temp ~ Category) %>%
    generate(reps = 1000, type = "bootstrap") %>%
    calculate(stat = "diff in means", order = c("contemporary", "historical"))

diff_in_temp_ci <- 
     diff_in_temp_bootstrap_dist %>% 
     get_confidence_interval(level = 0.95, type = "percentile")

diff_in_temp_ci_plot <- diff_in_temp_bootstrap_dist %>%
    visualize(bins = 10) +
    shade_ci(diff_in_temp_ci) +
    xlab("Difference between sample means (°C)") +
    scale_x_continuous(limits = c(-0.3, 2.5)) +
    geom_vline(xintercept = 0, size = 2, linetype = "dashed") +
    theme(text = element_text(size = 20))

diff_in_temp_ci_plot

Figure 4. Figure of simulated bootstrap distribution of confidence interval of the sample statistic.

Notice that the value 0 is not included in our confidence interval, again suggesting that $\mu_{ct}$ and $\mu_{ht}$ are truly different.

Table 3 summarizes the value we obtained for this test statistic. 95% confidence interval.

Test Statistic Observed Test Statistic p-value Lower CI Upper CI
$\bar{x}_{ct} - \bar{x}_{ht}$ 1.258 <0.001 1.048 1.465

Table 3. Table of the estimates for test statistic - difference in mean temperature by simulation.

Temperature - Asymptotic Two Samples T-Test¶

We further investigate the difference between mean temperatures using the asymptotic method.

In [8]:
temp_contemporary <- station_temp %>%
    filter(Category == "contemporary")

temp_historical <- station_temp %>%
    filter(Category == "historical")

temp_t_test <- tidy(
    t.test(temp_contemporary$Mean_Temp, temp_historical$Mean_Temp, alternative = "two.sided"))

Table 4 summarizes the result of the t-test. We can see that the estimates of the difference in mean temperature between historical and contemporary data obtained from the two-sample t-test are very similar to the result we obtained from bootstrap simulation. The 95% confidence interval for the observed test statistic does not include 0 as well.

Test Statistic Observed Test Statistic p-value Lower CI Upper CI
$\bar{x}_{ct} - \bar{x}_{ht}$ 1.258 <0.001 1.055 1.461

Table 4. Table of the estimates for test statistic - difference in mean temperature by asymptotic.

Looking at the 95% confidence interval and the p-value for the observed test statistic from both bootstrap and t-test, there is enough evidence to conclude that the difference between historical and contemporary temperature is not zero. We further demonstrate the parameter difference between the two categories.

Temperature - Bootstrapping Simulation for Point Estimates¶

From our hypothesis testing, we conclude that there is a difference between the two group's mean temperature. Now we are looking at the distribution of each group and we aim to explore how much they different by.
We use a bootstrap distribution to estimate the standard error in the point estimate and generated a 95% confidence interval for each point estimate.

Precipitation¶

The United Nations (n.d.-a) states that due to climate change, destructive storms have become more intense and more frequent in many regions. The reason for this is as temperature rises, more moisture evaporates, which leads to extreme rainfall and flooding, causing more destructive storms. Can we see this claimed difference in yearly extreme rainfall between historical and contemporary data at Abbotsford A weather station? We first subset the Total_Rain to obtain the highest yearly rainfall. The hypothesis we will be testing here is:

$$H_0^{2}: \mu_{cr} - \mu_{hr} = 0$$

$$H_A^{2}: \mu_{cr} - \mu_{hr} \neq 0$$

We generate a box plot and its sample distribution to visualize the sample.

Extreme Rainfall - Bootstrap Simulation¶

We first test by simulation. We calculate the observed test statistic, then generate a simulation from the null distribution. We further obtain the P-value. The following codes demonstrate the steps:

In [13]:
set.seed(100)
options(repr.plot.width = 10, repr.plot.height = 6)

obs_diff_in_rainfall <- station_rain_yearly_max %>%
    specify(formula = max_rain ~ Category) %>%
    calculate(stat = "diff in means", order = c("contemporary", "historical"))

null_diff_in_rainfall <- station_rain_yearly_max %>%
    specify(formula = max_rain ~ Category) %>%
    hypothesize(null = "independence") %>%
    generate(reps = 10000, type = "permute") %>%
    calculate(stat = "diff in means", order = c("contemporary", "historical"))

diff_in_rainfall_plot <- null_diff_in_rainfall %>%
    visualize(bins = 10) +
    shade_p_value(obs_stat = obs_diff_in_rainfall, direction = "both") +
    xlab("Difference between sample means (mm)") +
    theme(text = element_text(size = 20))
diff_in_rainfall_plot

p_value <- null_diff_in_rainfall %>%
    get_p_value(obs_stat = obs_diff_in_rainfall, direction = "both")
# p_value

Figure 8. Simulation distribution and P-value of the yearly maximum rainfall hypothesis test.

We obtain a p_value of 0.474, so we do not reject the null hypothesis at 5% significant level. We further compute the 95% confidence interval of this test statistic.

diff_in_rainfall_bootstrap_dist <- station_rain_yearly_max %>%

Extreme Rainfall - Asymptotic Two Samples T-Test¶

We further investigate the difference between the mean of maximum yearly rainfall using the asymptotic method.

In [15]:
rain_contemporary <- station_rain_yearly_max %>%
    filter(Category == "contemporary") %>%
    pull(max_rain)
rain_historical <- station_rain_yearly_max %>%
    filter(Category == "historical")%>%
    pull(max_rain)

Max_rain_t_test <- tidy(t.test(x = rain_contemporary, y = rain_historical, alternative = "two.sided"))
Test Statistic Observed Test Statistic p-value Lower CI Upper CI
$\bar{x}_{cr} \;- \;\bar{x}_{hr}$ 3.505 0.481 -6.485 13.495

Table 7. Table of the estimates for test statistic - difference in yearly max rainfall by asymptotic.

As a result, we have confirmed that we do not have enough evidence to reject the null hypothesis.

Results¶

In the first part of this report, we test the:
Null Hypothesis: The difference in population mean of the contemporary daily mean temperature and the historical daily mean temperature is zero. $H_0^{1}: \mu_{ct} - \mu_{ht} = 0$
Alternative Hypothesis: The difference in population mean of the contemporary daily mean temperature and the historical daily mean temperature is not zero. $H_A^{1}: \mu_{ct} - \mu_{ht} \neq 0$

Table 8 summarizes the p-value and the 95% confidence interval results by simulation and asymptotic for the temperature variable.

Test Statistic Observed Test Statistic Method p-value Lower CI Upper CI
$\bar{x}_{ct} - \bar{x}_{ht}$ 1.258 Simulation <0.001 1.048 1.465
$\bar{x}_{ct} - \bar{x}_{ht}$ 1.258 Asymptotic <0.001 1.055 1.461

Table 8. Table of the estimates for test statistic - difference in mean temperature.

The p-value is < 0.001, we reject the null hypothesis $H_0^1$ in favor of $H_A^1$ at the 5% significant level. There is a significant difference between $\mu_{ct}$ and $\mu_{ht}$.

In the second part of this report, we test the:
Null Hypothesis: The difference in population mean of the contemporary maximum yearly rainfall and the historical maximum yearly rainfall is zero. $H_0^{2}: \mu_{cr} - \mu_{hr} = 0$
Alternative Hypothesis: The difference in population mean of the contemporary maximum yearly rainfall and the historical maximum yearly rainfall is not zero. $H_A^{2}: \mu_{cr} - \mu_{hr} \neq 0$

Table 9 summarizes the p-value and the 95% confidence interval results by simulation and asymptotic for the rainfall variable.

Test Statistic Observed Test Statistic Method p-value Lower CI Upper CI
$\bar{x}_{cr} - \bar{x}_{hr}$ 3.505 Simulation 0.474 -6.005 13.008
$\bar{x}_{ct} - \bar{x}_{ht}$ 3.505 Asymptotic 0.481 -6.485 13.495

Table 9. Table of the estimates for test statistic - difference in rainfall.

The p-value is larger than 0.05, we cannot reject the null hypothesis $H_0^2$ at the 5% significant level. There is no significant difference between $\mu_{cr}$ and $\mu_{hr}$.

we conclude:

Based on the first hypothesis test, we notice that there is barely any difference between p-value with bootstrap simulation test and asymptotic two samples t-test, and the 95% confidence intervals by the two test methods are approximately the same. As the sample size in the first test is large enough, the results of bootstrap simulation test and asymptotic two samples t-test are extremely close.

According to the second hypothesis test, we notice that there is a small difference in p-values between the two test methods, which is possibly due to the small sample size. We notice that the 95% confidence interval by the asymptotic two samples t-test is wider than that by the bootstrap simulation test. We believe this is due to the simulation method applies a normal distribution whereas the t-test applies a t-distribution. A t-distribution has heavier tails that generate a wider confidence interval. However, there is not enough evidence to conclude which test method is better, because we don't have enough information on the population.

Discussion¶

Summary And Implications of Findings

This study serves as an empirical analysis of climate change for the Abbotsford region. According to the preliminary data visualization, we found out that there is a difference in mean temperature between historical and contemporary data sets. We then performed hypothesis testing accordingly with a significance level of 0.05. Both simulation-based bootstrap and asymptotic t-test showed a similar result for mean temperature. We conclude that there is sufficient evidence that the true population parameter is significantly different from the specified value in which the observed test statistic of 1.258 showed that there is a rise in mean temperature. It may be a shred of evidence to support the statement that the climate is changing. It may impact how the municipalities plan to adjust their local agriculture industry facing the rising temperature in the future.

However, the means were similar for yearly maximum precipitation although there were more extreme values in the contemporary dataset. For both simulation-based bootstrap and asymptotic t-test, the test is insignificant at the given significance level. Therefore, we failed to reject the null hypothesis, which indicates that there is insufficient evidence to conclude that there is a difference in the mean of maximum yearly rainfall between contemporary and historical datasets. The probability of finding a value more or as extreme as our observed test statistic of 3.505 is pretty high. From this finding, there is no significant change in maximum yearly rainfall, so we cannot conclude that there were more severe storms or droughts in recent years compared to the past years.

Alignment With Expectation

The results align with our hypothesis that there is a difference in mean temperature. We are now confident that the mean temperature keeps rising. The result for mean precipitation also align with the preliminary finding.

Suggestions For Future Study

For future studies we would like to examine whether other stations may show similar/different results (eg. Can our study be generalized to a broader population outside of the Abbotsford region?). There are many factors other than temperature and precipitation that may be interesting to observe (eg. What other dataset do we need to include for such generalization to be valid and meaningful?).
